Definition: This task is about using the specified sentence and converting the sentence to Resource Description Framework (RDF) triplets of the form (subject, predicate object). The RDF triplets generated must be such that the triplets accurately capture the structure and semantics of the input sentence. The input is a sentence and the output is a list of triplets of the form [subject, predicate, object] that capture the relationships present in the sentence. When a sentence has more than 1 RDF triplet possible, the output must contain all of them.

Positive Examples.input: University of mississippi was in the selc new conference.
Positive Examples.explanation: This is a good example since the subject of the sentence is University of Mississipi and it is connected to the object (SELC) via the predicate (new_conference). The output RDF captures the key elements of the sentence and is easily interpretable as well.

Positive Examples.input: The nickname of the  team of University of Nebraska at Omaha is mavericks.
Positive Examples.explanation: This is a good example since the subject of the sentence is University of Nebraska and it is connected to the object (Mavericks) via the predicate (NICKNAME). The output RDF captures the key elements of the sentence and is easily interpretable as well.

Positive Examples.input: Chris Hodgson aged 26 was eliminated from the compassion for food during week 6.
Positive Examples.explanation: This is a good example since the different RDF triplets detected accurately detect the different facts interacting in this sentence. For example, the first 2 RDF triplets are easily connected together using the third RDF triplet.

Negative Examples.input: Edwards represented the North Metropolitan Province.
Negative Examples.explanation: This sentence is a bad example since even though it got the subject (Edwards) and predicate (PROVINCE) correct, it did not correctly detect the object (North Metropolitan)

Negative Examples.input: Li Qiaoxian of China had a preliminary rank of 6.
Negative Examples.explanation: This sentence is a bad example since even though it got the object (6) correct, but got the subject (Li Qiaoxian of China) and predicate (preliminary rank) partially correct.

Negative Examples.input: Say It Again was released in 1986.
Negative Examples.explanation: This sentence is a bad example since even though it got all of the subject, object and predicate incorrect. In fact this sentence does not accurately capture the input sentence at all. It is unlikely that models trained using such statements can learn anything useful.
